&lt;p&gt;Everyone who contributed to the &lt;a href="https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/909377477/rails-composer-with-rails-tutorials"&gt;Kickstarter campaign&lt;/a&gt; deserves big thanks, as well. It&amp;rsquo;s the people who purchase the &lt;a href="https://tutorials.railsapps.org/"&gt;Capstone Rails Tutorials&lt;/a&gt; or who contributed to the Kickstarter campaign who keep the RailsApps project alive.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please try the new feature and let me know if it needs improvement. You can open a &lt;a href="https://github.com/RailsApps/rails-composer/issues"&gt;GitHub issue&lt;/a&gt; and give me your feedback.&lt;/p&gt;</description><link>https://blog.railsapps.org/post/132666060115</link><guid>https://blog.railsapps.org/post/132666060115</guid><pubDate>Fri, 06 Nov 2015 06:58:21 -0800</pubDate></item><item><title>New CSS Framework Filename</title><description>&lt;p&gt;All the RailsApps example applications add either the Bootstrap or Foundation front-end frameworks using a file &lt;code&gt;framework_and_overrides.css.scss&lt;/code&gt;. Files in the folder &lt;code&gt;app/assets/stylesheets&lt;/code&gt; are loaded in alphabetical order unless the manifest in &lt;code&gt;application.css.scss&lt;/code&gt; specifies the files by name.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Today I added a custom CSS file to a project with filename that preceded &lt;code&gt;framework_and_overrides.css.scss&lt;/code&gt; in alphabetical order. My custom CSS rules were overridden by the Bootstrap CSS, which is not what I wanted. I realized I could remove the &lt;code&gt;*= require_tree .&lt;/code&gt; directive in the &lt;code&gt;application.css.scss&lt;/code&gt; manifest and specify the files to load in the order I wanted. It&amp;rsquo;s easier to rename the &lt;code&gt;framework_and_overrides.css.scss&lt;/code&gt; as &lt;code&gt;1st_load_framework.css.scss&lt;/code&gt; and have it load first, automatically.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;ve changed the &lt;a href="https://github.com/RailsApps/rails_layout"&gt;rails_layout&lt;/a&gt; gem to use the new &lt;code&gt;1st_load_framework.css.scss&lt;/code&gt; filename. I&amp;rsquo;ll also change the filename in all the RailsApps example applications. I hope this doesn&amp;rsquo;t make a mess for anyone. I think the change is harmless and will simply the process of adding custom CSS files to RailsApps starter applications.&lt;/p&gt;</description><link>https://blog.railsapps.org/post/131408512345</link><guid>https://blog.railsapps.org/post/131408512345</guid><pubDate>Sun, 18 Oct 2015 03:08:42 -0700</pubDate></item><item><title>Successful Kickstarter</title><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="https://64.media.tumblr.com/a6712a6741263aead55cf84bf0793913/tumblr_inline_nwet0b2kgB1qkyz8s_540.png" alt=""/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

